The heat in terms of having their decision-making furiously examined by the public is currently on the Proteas management, but the Cricket South Africa (CSA) suits will be back in the spotlight later this month when they have to consider the report on the domestic structure of the game. While the board has managed to repel all the many calls for them to stand down after their leadership sent South African cricket plummeting to the brink of the abyss, the focus should now be on the 14-strong Members Council, made up of the provincial presidents. It is they who will...